     <p style="font-size:17px;font-weight:500">&quot; At The Chai Dhaba, we follow the standard Tea Preparation System keeping in mind that we have to maintain Quality, Taste, Steeping Time, Boiling Time and its ingredients&quot;</p>
     <img src="img/Kinkeliba_tea_preparation.jpg" style="width:200px;height:150px;border-radius:50%" />
        <br />
        <p class="auto-style1">
            <strong>ISO 3103</strong></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <b><span>ISO 3103</span></b><span>&nbsp;is a standard published by the&nbsp;</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Organization_for_Standardization" title="International Organization for Standardization"><span>International Organization for Standardization</span></a><span>&nbsp;(commonly referred to as ISO), specifying a standardized method for&nbsp;</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tea#Preparation" title="Tea"><span>brewing tea</span></a><o:p></o:p></p>
        <p style="text-align: center;">
            <strong>PREPARATION OF TEA ACCORDING TO ISO 3103 STANDARD</strong>&nbsp;</p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span>To maintain consistent results, the following are recommendations given by the standard:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <![if !supportLists]><span>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><![endif]><span>The pot should be white porcelain or&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ceramic_glaze" title="Ceramic glaze">glazed</a>&nbsp;earthenware and have a partly&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serration" title="Serration">serrated edge</a>.&nbsp; It should have a&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lid_(container)" title="Lid (container)">lid</a>&nbsp;that fits loosely inside the pot.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <![if !supportLists]><span>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><![endif]><span>If a large pot is used, it should hold a maximum of 310&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Litre" title="Litre">ml</a>&nbsp;(±8&nbsp;ml) and must weigh 200&nbsp;g (±10&nbsp;g).<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <![if !supportLists]><span>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><![endif]><span>If a small pot is used, it should hold a maximum of 150&nbsp;ml (±4&nbsp;ml) and must weigh 118&nbsp;g (±10&nbsp;g).<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <![if !supportLists]><span>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><![endif]><span>2&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gram" title="Gram">grams</a>&nbsp;of tea (measured to ±2% accuracy) per 100&nbsp;ml boiling water is placed into the pot.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <![if !supportLists]><span>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><![endif]><span>Freshly boiling water is poured into the pot within 4–6&nbsp;mm of the brim. Allow 20 seconds for water to cool.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <![if !supportLists]><span>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><![endif]><span>The water should be similar to the drinking water where the tea will be consumed.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <![if !supportLists]><span>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><![endif]><span>Brewing time is six minutes.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <![if !supportLists]><span>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><![endif]><span>The brewed tea is then poured into a white porcelain or glazed earthenware bowl.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <![if !supportLists]><span>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><![endif]><span>If a large bowl is used, it must have a capacity of 380&nbsp;ml and weigh 200&nbsp;g (±20&nbsp;g).<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <![if !supportLists]><span>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><![endif]><span>If a small bowl is used, it must have a capacity of 200&nbsp;ml and weigh 105&nbsp;g (±20&nbsp;g).<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <![if !supportLists]><span>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><![endif]><span>If the test involves milk, then it is added before pouring the infused tea unless that is contrary to the organisation&#39;s normal practice.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <![if !supportLists]><span>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><![endif]><span>If milk is added after the pouring of tea, it is best added when the liquid is between 65-80°C.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <![if !supportLists]><span>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><![endif]><span>5&nbsp;ml of milk for the large bowl, or 2.5&nbsp;ml for the small bowl, is used.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <br />
        <br />
        <p style="text-align: center;">
            <strong>GENERAL METHOD OF PREPARATION OF TEA</strong></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <strong>Select Type of Tea you want to Prepare</strong></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span>First of all we you have to decide that what kind of tea you want to prepare, like, Normal Tea, Black Tea, Green Tea, Masala Tea, Ginger Tea or Tulsi Tea. The different quality and taste of tea available in market.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span style="font-weight: 700">Use Good Water<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span>When making any tea, be sure you begin with good water, it makes up over 90 % of the end product. Water quality and taste vary greatly between locales. If your water tastes really good out of the tap, chances are it will make good tea. If there is a noticeable unpleasant taste (metallic, chlorine, earthiness, etc.) it will come through in the tea. You can use Mineral Water or filtered water from high quality machine like Aquaguard or Kent.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span style="font-weight: 700">Heat the Pot<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span>Pour a small amount of hot water into the pot to warm it before beginning to make your tea. For best results, always make tea with fresh water, not water that has been previously boiled or has been sitting around.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span style="font-weight: 700">Measure the Tea<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span>The standard guideline for tea is to use one rounded, measuring teaspoon (3 grams) of tea for each 8 ounce (236 ml) cup of water. When measuring, take the leaf size into account. The approximate weight of the tea should be 3 grams of tea per cup.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span style="font-weight: 700">Measure the Water Temp<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span>Different teas require different water temperatures for steeping. Using water that is too hot results in bitter tea and is probably the most common error people make when preparing tea. You can use a thermometer or visual cues to gauge water temperature.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span style="font-weight: 700">Time the Steep<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span>Different teas require different steep times. Refer to the instructions on the bag for the specific steep time for each tea. Avoid steeping tea longer than recommended. If tea steeps too long it often becomes bitter<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span style="font-weight: 700">Leaf Expansion<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span>All teas require room for the leaf to expand as it steeps. Whatever preparation method you use make sure there is enough room for the leaf to expand 3-5 times in size as it steeps. Brewing the leaves loose in the pot and then straining works well, as do tea infusers and T-sacs. The Chai Dahaba, do not recommend using tea balls as there is very little room for leaf expansion, meaning that the full tea flavor never gets released into the liquid.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span style="font-weight: 700">Stop the Steeping<o:p></o:p></span></p>
        <p class="text-left">
            <span>Once the tea has steeped for the proper amount of time, separate the leaves from the liquid. This stops the steeping process so the tea does not oversteep and become bitter. Using T-sacs or filters makes this step easy. When the leaves are removed, the tea is ready to be served. <o:p></o:p></span>
        </p>
